Please update the [stock image confluence page|https://confluence.atlassian.com/bamboocloud/stock-images-737184550.html] with a note that explains that:

{quote} Atlassian images are PV-only. However there's one hidden HVM image in US EAST, that we don't show in the UI. More information on this can be found [on this comment|https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/BAM-12121?focusedCommentId=770131&page=com.atlassian.jira.plugin.system.issuetabpanels:comment-tabpanel#comment-770131].

{code}
image.US_EAST_1.EBS.x86_64.linux.HVM.Ubuntu=ami-55a3ec3f
{code}

Users should be able to [copy it over to US WEST|http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/CopyingAMIs.html]. However stock images will still be PV until https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/BAM-16190 is rolled out.{quote}

Also, to point to the following url to give users the information on how to convert the image themselves:
http://stackoverflow.com/questions/24330721/amazon-ec2-how-to-convert-an-existing-pv-ami-to-hvm

That would save users a lot of time and will allow them (if needed) the ability to still use the stock images currently.

We use Bamboo cloud and a server running Bamboo agent. The users create plans with Bitbucket repositories and enter their passwords to Bamboo. Anyone, who has access to the server running Bamboo agent may read users passwords in the files like
{noformat}
PROJECT/.git/logs/refs/heads/master
{noformat}

Define a build which creates a shared artifact which has some accented characters e.g. ūmläüt.txt.
Run an export, which includes the Artifacts.
{code}
Export has failed. Errors encountered while exporting: artifacts/TESTPROJECT-UML/shared/build-00001/umlaut_test/ūmläüt.txt (java.io.CharConversionException: artifacts/TESTPROJECT-UML/shared/build-00001/umlaut_test/ūmläüt.txt (entry name not encodable with IBM437)).
{code}
After removing the Artifact, the export was successful.

This issue is extremely similar to BAM-9114

Bamboo ant target is:
{code}
build -Dbuild.number="${bamboo.buildNumber}" -Dbuild.key="${bamboo.buildKey}" -Dbuild.name="Integration Build"
{code}

This gets translated ( as seen into the log ):
{code}
Beginning to execute external process for build 'NextGen EDA - Integration Build (v2) - Default Job'<br /> ... running command line: <br />
C:\apache-ant-1.7.1\bin\ant.bat<br />  -Djava.io.tmpdir=C:\WINDOWS\TEMP\NGEDA-INTV2-JOB1<br />
  -f<br />  build.xml<br />  build<br />  -Dbuild.number="8827"<br /> 
-Dbuild.key="NGEDA-INTV2-JOB1"<br />  -Dbuild.name="Integration Build"<br /> ... in: C:\bamboo-agent-home\xml-data\build-dir\NGEDA-INTV2-JOB1<br /> ... 
{code}

The build goes through for the *build* target and pass successfully but then immediately fails with the error:
{code}
BUILD FAILED
error	30-Jan-2012 13:15:08	Target "Build" does not exist in the project "project.name.here"
{code}

There is indeed no *Build* target - what happened is bamboo interpreted the property *-Dbuild.name="Integration Build"* as *-Dbuild.name=Integration* and *Build* as a new target.

Renaming *-Dbuild.name="Integration Build"* into *-Dbuild.name="Integration_Build"* fixed the issue.

This bug is seen at least in the Ant task and prevents any space in command line arguments ( even surrounded by quotes).

This would be a great feature for teams that do not want to link their builds via child/parent relations or dependencies. It would allow for the building of multiple source components to a single distribution package but still allow for release management from one project in JIRA.

From original issue:
{quote}
We have multiple components that make up a bigger release, which each have their own separate build. It would be great, if when we "release" a version that we could reference multiple plans.
{quote}
